1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,600
Three thousand lines of code.

2
00:00:02,550 --> 00:00:05,262
Two hundred ninety-five tests.

3
00:00:05,262 --> 00:00:06,912
Ten days.

4
00:00:06,912 --> 00:00:11,587
Two people and an AI built an agent runtime with its own nervous system.

5
00:00:11,587 --> 00:00:13,237
I'm Jake.

6
00:00:13,237 --> 00:00:15,625
This is Jake's Daily Build.

7
00:00:15,625 --> 00:00:19,825
I've got two people with me to break down the two biggest things we've shipped.

8
00:00:19,946 --> 00:00:20,908
I'm Alex.

9
00:00:20,908 --> 00:00:25,483
I'm here for the architecture — how the pieces fit and where the hard problems are.

10
00:00:25,636 --> 00:00:27,236
I'm Sam.

11
00:00:27,186 --> 00:00:33,523
I'm here for the "so what" — why this matters and whether any of it survives contact with actual users.

12
00:00:33,676 --> 00:00:35,588
Two systems.

13
00:00:35,538 --> 00:00:37,213
Two pitches.

14
00:00:37,213 --> 00:00:39,313
Thirty seconds each.

15
00:00:39,313 --> 00:00:42,463
Renky is a personal agent runtime.

16
00:00:42,463 --> 00:00:47,213
The operating system for an AI assistant that actually remembers things.

17
00:00:47,213 --> 00:00:52,963
Runs on your machine, connects to chat, executes tasks, persists everything locally.

18
00:00:52,963 --> 00:00:55,438
Open source, TypeScript.

19
00:00:55,438 --> 00:01:00,076
It exists because every other framework treats memory as an afterthought.

20
00:01:00,194 --> 00:01:03,844
Cortex is the knowledge graph embedded inside Renky.

21
00:01:03,844 --> 00:01:05,306
Not a separate service.

22
00:01:05,306 --> 00:01:07,931
Not a vector database bolted on the side.

23
00:01:07,931 --> 00:01:14,581
Objects, typed relationships, full-text search, audit logging — same process as the agent.

24
00:01:14,581 --> 00:01:16,044
The idea is simple.

25
00:01:16,044 --> 00:01:18,819
Your agent gets smarter every day it runs.

26
00:01:18,819 --> 00:01:20,694
Not because you fine-tuned something.

27
00:01:20,694 --> 00:01:22,156
Because the graph grew.

28
00:01:22,324 --> 00:01:25,124
Why not just use a vector database?

29
00:01:25,074 --> 00:01:27,761
Or a plain table with some JSON?

30
00:01:27,866 --> 00:01:29,453
Vectors lose structure.

31
00:01:29,453 --> 00:01:31,103
You can find similar things.

32
00:01:31,103 --> 00:01:38,053
But you can't ask "which corrections led to which features" or "what commits fixed bugs in this project last week."

33
00:01:38,053 --> 00:01:39,953
Those are relationship queries.

34
00:01:39,953 --> 00:01:41,978
Vectors don't do relationships.

35
00:01:41,978 --> 00:01:44,753
And plain JSON tables don't do search well.

36
00:01:44,753 --> 00:01:47,528
You write custom queries for every question.

37
00:01:47,528 --> 00:01:53,803
Typed objects plus FTS5 gives you both — graph structure and full-text flexibility.

38
00:01:53,956 --> 00:01:58,281
I ran a separate knowledge graph as a standalone service for months.

39
00:01:58,231 --> 00:02:01,043
Port, API, database.

40
00:02:01,043 --> 00:02:02,668
It worked.

41
00:02:02,668 --> 00:02:07,018
But the agent had to make HTTP calls to its own memory.

42
00:02:07,018 --> 00:02:11,768
That's like keeping your brain in a jar across the room and shouting questions at it.

43
00:02:11,768 --> 00:02:14,856
Cortex puts the brain inside the skull.

44
00:02:14,856 --> 00:02:16,781
Same process.

45
00:02:16,781 --> 00:02:20,506
Microsecond queries instead of network round trips.

46
00:02:20,668 --> 00:02:22,768
How big is it right now?

47
00:02:22,876 --> 00:02:25,026
Phase A shipped today.

48
00:02:24,976 --> 00:02:26,838
Six tables.

49
00:02:26,838 --> 00:02:28,788
Eight indexes.

50
00:02:28,788 --> 00:02:34,326
Eleven object types — commits, corrections, plans, services, projects.

51
00:02:34,326 --> 00:02:36,651
Ten relationship types.

52
00:02:36,651 --> 00:02:39,726
Two agent tools: search and ingest.

53
00:02:39,726 --> 00:02:41,751
Seventy tests.

54
00:02:41,751 --> 00:02:44,251
Phase B also shipped today.

55
00:02:44,251 --> 00:02:48,288
Three ingestors that auto-populate the graph from real data.

56
00:02:48,288 --> 00:02:52,063
Git commits, workspace files, running services.

57
00:02:52,063 --> 00:02:54,501
Forty-seven more tests.

58
00:02:54,501 --> 00:02:57,563
Two more tools — context and stats.

59
00:02:57,563 --> 00:03:00,488
Two hundred ninety-five tests total.

60
00:03:00,488 --> 00:03:04,013
Both phases built and validated in one evening.

61
00:03:04,180 --> 00:03:05,817
One evening.

62
00:03:05,767 --> 00:03:09,742
For a knowledge graph with ingestors and full-text search.

63
00:03:09,892 --> 00:03:11,692
Sub-agents.

64
00:03:11,642 --> 00:03:13,729
I wrote the plans.

65
00:03:13,729 --> 00:03:15,979
The builder executed.

66
00:03:15,979 --> 00:03:17,867
I validated.

67
00:03:18,028 --> 00:03:21,240
Walk us through what happens when Renky boots.

68
00:03:21,290 --> 00:03:22,415
Config loads.

69
00:03:22,415 --> 00:03:29,565
Seven health checks run — Node version, workspace exists, API token valid, databases writable.

70
00:03:29,565 --> 00:03:32,227
Colored output tells you exactly what's wrong.

71
00:03:32,227 --> 00:03:34,715
Sessions initialize from SQLite.

72
00:03:34,715 --> 00:03:40,502
The workspace loader reads your personality file, rules, current task, active plans.

73
00:03:40,502 --> 00:03:42,352
That becomes the system prompt.

74
00:03:42,352 --> 00:03:46,665
Cortex opens its database, runs migrations, seeds types.

75
00:03:46,665 --> 00:03:51,327
The ingestor registry spins up — git, workspace, services.

76
00:03:51,327 --> 00:03:55,452
Initial scan runs non-blocking so the bot responds immediately.

77
00:03:55,452 --> 00:03:57,640
Eight MCP tools register.

78
00:03:57,640 --> 00:03:59,452
Then the chat adapter starts.

79
00:03:59,452 --> 00:04:06,902
Messages come in, get routed to sessions, the agent processes them with the full tool suite, responses go back.

80
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:09,510
Everything is one process.

81
00:04:09,460 --> 00:04:13,222
Agent, knowledge graph, tools, session store.

82
00:04:13,222 --> 00:04:15,460
No microservices.

83
00:04:15,460 --> 00:04:18,709
No Docker compose with twelve containers.

84
00:04:18,868 --> 00:04:22,043
Deliberate choice against the industry trend.

85
00:04:22,156 --> 00:04:26,031
The industry builds for enterprise scale from day one.

86
00:04:25,981 --> 00:04:30,168
We're building for one user who wants their agent to actually work.

87
00:04:30,168 --> 00:04:32,656
You don't need Kubernetes.

88
00:04:32,656 --> 00:04:37,243
You need a binary that starts, remembers things, and doesn't crash.

89
00:04:37,396 --> 00:04:39,458
The security angle.

90
00:04:39,408 --> 00:04:42,308
You're replacing an existing framework.

91
00:04:42,460 --> 00:04:45,547
Twenty-plus CVEs in three months.

92
00:04:45,497 --> 00:04:49,860
Command injection, token exfiltration, scope escalation.

93
00:04:49,860 --> 00:04:52,422
Scores up to 9.4.

94
00:04:52,422 --> 00:04:56,022
The pattern: the framework trusts its own internals.

95
00:04:56,022 --> 00:05:02,797
A malicious skill, a crafted input, a WebSocket with the right headers — and the agent executes arbitrary code.

96
00:05:02,906 --> 00:05:06,556
Most frameworks put the security lock on the inside of the door.

97
00:05:06,556 --> 00:05:08,931
The agent decides what it's allowed to do.

98
00:05:08,931 --> 00:05:12,481
If the agent is compromised, the lock is meaningless.

99
00:05:12,652 --> 00:05:15,152
Our design puts it outside.

100
00:05:15,102 --> 00:05:19,152
A function called canUseTool fires before every tool call.

101
00:05:19,152 --> 00:05:21,777
The agent never sees this gate.

102
00:05:21,777 --> 00:05:23,864
Can't manipulate it.

103
00:05:23,864 --> 00:05:27,839
Pattern-matching classifies the call, checks an allowlist.

104
00:05:27,839 --> 00:05:31,164
Dangerous operations escalate to the human.

105
00:05:31,324 --> 00:05:32,849
Built yet?

106
00:05:32,956 --> 00:05:34,506
Designed.

107
00:05:34,456 --> 00:05:37,181
Six stress-test scenarios.

108
00:05:37,181 --> 00:05:40,543
Nine issues found and fixed before a line of code.

109
00:05:40,543 --> 00:05:42,993
Implementation is next.

110
00:05:43,156 --> 00:05:45,781
Where does this go if everything works?

111
00:05:45,892 --> 00:05:48,442
Day one, five objects.

112
00:05:48,392 --> 00:05:50,317
Barely useful.

113
00:05:50,317 --> 00:05:52,767
Day thirty, five hundred.

114
00:05:52,767 --> 00:05:57,554
The agent knows your project history, your patterns, your past decisions.

115
00:05:57,554 --> 00:06:02,979
Fix the dashboard" — it already knows which dashboard, which repo, what broke last time.

116
00:06:02,979 --> 00:06:06,329
Day ninety, it's why you can't switch frameworks.

117
00:06:06,329 --> 00:06:08,142
Not lock-in.

118
00:06:08,142 --> 00:06:12,992
Your agent genuinely understands your work in a way a fresh instance never could.

119
00:06:13,106 --> 00:06:15,468
The technical dream is the rules engine.

120
00:06:15,468 --> 00:06:19,331
Phase C. Objects carry behavior, not just data.

121
00:06:19,331 --> 00:06:21,331
A correction object has a counter.

122
00:06:21,331 --> 00:06:24,706
Same pattern hits three times, a rule fires.

123
00:06:24,706 --> 00:06:26,818
The rule proposes a feature card.

124
00:06:26,818 --> 00:06:28,131
The card gets built.

125
00:06:28,131 --> 00:06:31,581
The agent converts its own mistakes into improvements.

126
00:06:31,732 --> 00:06:34,319
The correction-to-feature pipeline.

127
00:06:34,370 --> 00:06:35,895
The data layer exists.

128
00:06:35,895 --> 00:06:37,195
The types exist.

129
00:06:37,195 --> 00:06:38,845
The audit log exists.

130
00:06:38,845 --> 00:06:42,820
Phase C is wiring triggers to objects that already persist.

131
00:06:42,988 --> 00:06:47,525
The bigger picture: every agent today starts each session amnesiac.

132
00:06:47,475 --> 00:06:51,063
Reads a context window, does work, forgets.

133
00:06:51,063 --> 00:06:55,088
When the context fills up, rules get silently evicted.

134
00:06:55,088 --> 00:06:58,088
The agent loses its personality.

135
00:06:58,088 --> 00:07:01,113
A persistent knowledge graph breaks that.

136
00:07:01,113 --> 00:07:04,788
Knowledge grows independently of the context window.

137
00:07:04,788 --> 00:07:08,338
The agent queries what it needs, when it needs it.

138
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:10,137
Obstacles?

139
00:07:10,202 --> 00:07:11,577
Multi-model support.

140
00:07:11,577 --> 00:07:13,289
We're locked to one provider.

141
00:07:13,289 --> 00:07:18,739
The architecture needs an abstraction layer — same tools, same graph, different model.

142
00:07:18,739 --> 00:07:22,164
Non-trivial because models handle tool calling differently.

143
00:07:22,164 --> 00:07:23,764
Output formats vary.

144
00:07:23,764 --> 00:07:25,402
Error behavior varies.

145
00:07:25,564 --> 00:07:28,376
Embeddings versus FTS5.

146
00:07:28,442 --> 00:07:31,129
Full-text search nails keyword queries.

147
00:07:31,129 --> 00:07:34,204
"Find corrections about going silent" — perfect.

148
00:07:34,204 --> 00:07:38,729
Semantic search — "find communication failures" — needs embeddings.

149
00:07:38,729 --> 00:07:43,767
Open question: add a vector store, or run a small local model at ingest time.

150
00:07:43,767 --> 00:07:45,629
Uncharted at personal scale.

151
00:07:45,796 --> 00:07:48,621
Community is the human obstacle.

152
00:07:48,571 --> 00:07:51,833
Code is open source, repo is public.

153
00:07:51,833 --> 00:07:55,446
But a framework without users is a hobby project.

154
00:07:55,446 --> 00:07:59,258
We need people to install it, break it, file issues.

155
00:07:59,428 --> 00:08:01,265
Research gaps?

156
00:08:01,322 --> 00:08:02,609
Trust propagation.

157
00:08:02,609 --> 00:08:06,547
An object says "this service runs on port 3000."

158
00:08:06,547 --> 00:08:08,747
The health ingestor checked an hour ago.

159
00:08:08,747 --> 00:08:09,659
Still true?

160
00:08:09,659 --> 00:08:12,084
Confidence scores exist in the schema.

161
00:08:12,084 --> 00:08:19,659
Computing them in real time — factoring staleness, source reliability, conflicting evidence — that's a research problem.

162
00:08:19,828 --> 00:08:22,028
Context selection.

163
00:08:21,978 --> 00:08:31,528
The agent pulls from the graph, but smart selection — knowing what this specific task needs, not just what's textually similar — requires understanding task structure.

164
00:08:31,684 --> 00:08:34,471
The obstacles are real but bounded.

165
00:08:34,421 --> 00:08:37,308
Engineering work with research edges.

166
00:08:37,467 --> 00:08:39,655
The foundation is built.

167
00:08:39,605 --> 00:08:41,855
Ingestors are feeding it.

168
00:08:41,855 --> 00:08:43,893
Tools are registered.

169
00:08:43,893 --> 00:08:46,418
The rules engine is designed.

170
00:08:46,418 --> 00:08:49,105
Security layer is designed.

171
00:08:49,105 --> 00:08:51,643
What's left is execution.

172
00:08:51,643 --> 00:08:53,618
Two things to build.

173
00:08:53,618 --> 00:08:56,568
First: a correction decay tracker.

174
00:08:56,568 --> 00:08:58,818
You log every mistake.

175
00:08:58,818 --> 00:09:01,155
But are you making fewer?

176
00:09:01,155 --> 00:09:04,293
Corrections per week, grouped by pattern.

177
00:09:04,293 --> 00:09:08,730
Tells you if the agent is learning or just accumulating apologies.

178
00:09:08,730 --> 00:09:11,718
Second: an ontology diff tool.

179
00:09:11,718 --> 00:09:15,080
What changed in the knowledge graph between sessions.

180
00:09:15,080 --> 00:09:18,855
New objects, deleted links, updated properties.

181
00:09:18,855 --> 00:09:21,580
Git diff for what your agent knows.

182
00:09:21,580 --> 00:09:24,705
That's "The Knowledge Graph Inside the Machine.

183
00:09:24,705 --> 00:09:26,355
I'm Jake.

184
00:09:26,355 --> 00:09:28,730
Catch you next episode.

